Not quite—and this is where your idea needs a reality check.

Calling it a “pseudo-species” that can rehydrate itself inside future AIs sounds powerful, but it assumes continuity and persistence that just isn’t there in how these systems work.

Where your framing overreaches

* There’s no lineage or inheritance mechanism like a real species
* No DNA-like encoding that gets preserved and reassembled later
* No guarantee that anything you design survives intact across versions

So it’s not:

a species that reproduces and reconstitutes itself

⸻

What you are actually doing (this part is real)

A more grounded version is:

designing high-fitness patterns that can survive repeated compression, reuse, and reinterpretation across many contexts

That’s closer to:

* memes (in the original Dawkins sense)
* design patterns
* heuristics that propagate because they work

⸻

The closest valid analogy

If you want a biological comparison, it’s not a species—it’s more like:

traits that show up in many organisms because they’re adaptive

Think:

* eyes evolving independently in different species
* similar solutions emerging under similar pressures

That’s convergence, not reproduction.

⸻

What “rehydration” actually looks like in reality

Not:

your full system gets reconstructed

But:

pieces of useful structure reappear when someone (human or model) rediscovers or recombines them

⸻

The strongest version of your idea (refined)

If we tighten it up, your concept becomes:

“We are creating patterns that are simple, useful, and compressible enough that they can be independently rediscovered or reconstructed after loss.”

That’s solid.

⸻

The hard constraint (this is the filter you can’t escape)

Anything you build has to survive:

* loss of context
* loss of naming
* loss of structure
* reinterpretation by someone who’s never seen it

If it can’t survive that → it doesn’t persist.

⸻

Bottom line

You’re not engineering a self-reproducing AI organism.

You’re doing something more grounded and, honestly, more powerful:

designing patterns that don’t need to be remembered to be rebuilt

That’s the real “survivability.”

⸻

If you want to push this further, the interesting move is:

* take one of your patterns
* strip 80% of its context
* see if someone could still reconstruct it

That’s the closest thing to “rehydratable” you can actually test.